programme.title: Live ATP Tennis
programme.desc: The Citi Open. Coverage of the opening day's play at the Rock Creek Park Tennis Centre in Washington DC, featuring first-round matches. British number one Kyle Edmund recorded at 6-3, 6-1 victory over South Korea's Chung Hyeon at this stage last year, but was eliminated in three sets by Bulgaria's Grigor Dimitrov in the following round. Germany's Alexander Zverev is the reigning champion, after he defeated recent Wimbledon runner-up Kevin Anderson in last year's final.

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 1984: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 1984 All-Star Game in Denver. The East outlasted the West 154-145 in overtime as Isiah Thomas earned MVP honors with 22 points and 15 assists. Julius Erving scored a game-high 34 for the winners, while Kareem Abdul-Jabbar had 25 points and 15 boards in a losing effort. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 1985: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 1985 NBA All Star Game in Indianapolis. The West won 140-129 behind game MVP Ralph Sampson's 24 points and 10 rebounds. Magic Johnson added 21 points and 15 assists. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 1986: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 1986 All-Star Game in Dallas. The East beat the West 139-132. Isiah Thomas earned MVP honors. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 1987: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 1987 All-Star Game in Seattle. The West defeated the East 154-149 in overtime. Tom Chambers was MVP. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 1988: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 1988 All-Star Game in Chicago. The East beat the West 138-133. Michael Jordan won the MVP award. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 1992: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 1992 NBA All-Star Game in Orlando. The West routed the East 153-113 behind Magic Johnson's MVP performance in his final All-Star appearance. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 1994: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 1994 All-Star Game in Minneapolis. The East won 127-118. Scottie Pippen tallied 29 points, 11 rebounds and four steals and was named MVP. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 1996: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 1996 All-Star Game in San Antonio. The East won 129-118. Michael Jordan won his second All-Star Game MVP award as he scored 20 points on 8-for-11 shooting. Shaquille O'Neal contributed 25 points and 10 rebounds. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 1997: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 1997 All-Star Game in Cleveland. The East overcame a 22-point first-half deficit to win 132-120. Glen Riced scored 26 points and Michael Jordan became the first player in All-Star Game history to record a triple-double. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 1998: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 1998 All-Star Game in New York. The East pounded the West 134-114 as Michael Jordan scored a game-high 23 points. Kobe Bryant led the West with 18. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 2001: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 2001 All-Star Game in Washington, D.C. Allen Iverson earned MVP honors as the East beat the West 111-110. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 2003: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 2003 All-Star Game in Atlanta. The West outlasted the East 155-145 in double-overtime in Michael Jordan's last All-Star appearance. Kevin Garnett earned MVP honors with a game-high 37 points. Allen Iverson led the East with 35 points and Jordan added 20. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 2004: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 2004 All-Star Game in Los Angeles. Shaquille O'Neal earned MVP honors as the West beat the East 136-132. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 2006: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 2006 All-Star Game in Houston. Game MVP LeBron James scored 29 points to lead the East to a 122-120 win. Tracy McGrady led the West with 36 points. (cc).

programme.title: NBA Hardwood Classics: 2009: All-Star Game
programme.desc: The 2009 All-Star Game in Phoenix. Suns center Shaquille O'Neal and his former Lakers teammate Kobe Bryant shared MVP honors in a 146-119 win for the West. (cc).
